221F 101st Legislative Session 221
2026 South Dakota Legislature
Senate Bill 221
AMENDME NT 221F
FOR THE SENATE ENGROSSED BILL
Introduced by: Senator Karr
1 An Act to regulate the retail sale of nicotine products, and to provide a penalty
2 therefor.
3 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF SOUTH DAKOTA:
4 Section 1. That § 10-1-28.2 be AMENDED:
5 10-1-28.2. All lists of taxpayers, licensees, or applicants compiled by the
6 Department of Revenue are confidential, except licensees which were licensed under the
7 provisions of chapter 10-47B, 32-6B, 32-6C, 32-7A, or 32-7B, or sections 2 to 21 18,
8 inclusive, of this Act. It is a Class 2 misdemeanor to disclose any such list except to the
9 extent necessary to carry out the official duties of the department.
10 Section 2. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
11 Terms used in this chapter mean:
12 (1) "Alternative nicotine product," a noncombustible product containing nicotine from
13 any source or a nicotine analog that is intended for human consumption, whether
14 chewed, absorbed, dissolved, ingested, inhaled, or consumed by any other means.
15 The term does not include any vapor product or any product regulated as a drug,
16 food, or device by the United States Food and Drug Administration under the Food,
17 Drug and Cosmetic Act, 21 U.S.C chapter 9 subchapter V (January 1, 2026);
18 (2) "Department," the Department of Revenue;
19 (3) "Licensee," a person licensed under the provisions of this chapter;
20 (4) "Nicotine Analog," a substance that:
21 (a) Has a chemical structure substantially similar to the chemical structure of
22 nicotine;
23 (b) Has, or is represented to have, an effect on the central nervous system
24 similar to the chemical nicotine; and
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 2 221
1 (c) Is manufactured, formulated, sold, distributed, or marketed with the intent
2 to avoid the provisions of this chapter;
3 (3)(5) "Nicotine product," an alternative nicotine product, tobacco product, or vapor
4 product;
5 (4)(6) "Retailer," a person engaged in the business of selling a nicotine product to an
6 individual for any purpose other than resale;
7 (7) "Secretary," the secretary of the department;
8 (5)(8) "Tobacco product," cigarettes, cigars, snuff, chewing tobacco, and any other
9 products made up or composed of tobacco in whole or in part;
10 (6)(9) "Vapor product," a noncombustible product containing nicotine or a nicotine
11 analogue analog that employs a heating element, power source, electronic circuit,
12 or other electronic, chemical, or mechanical means, regardless of shape or size,
13 that which can be used to produce vapor or aerosol from nicotine or a nicotine
14 analog in a solution. The term includes, but is not limited to, any electronic
15 cigarette, electronic cigar, electronic cigarillo, electronic pipe, or similar product or
16 device, and a consumable nicotine or nicotine analog solution suitable for use in a
17 vapor product, and any component or part, whether sold with the product or
18 separately. The term does not include any product approved by the United States
19 Food and Drug Administration for sale as a tobacco cessation product and marketed
20 and sold solely for that purpose;
21 (7)(10) "Vending machine," a device that dispenses nicotine products to an individual
22 for any purpose other than resale. The term does not include a self-service display;
23 and
24 (8)(11) "Vending machine retailer," a person engaged in the business of selling a
25 nicotine product from vending machines.
26 Section 3. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
27 Any communication by, or on behalf of, the manufacturer, distributor, or retailer
28 of a nicotine product, which indicates that the product contains a nicotine analog,
29 constitutes presumptive evidence that the product contains a nicotine analog.
30 Section 4. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
31 A retailer shall secure a license under this chapter to sell a nicotine product in this
32 state. A separate application and a separate license are required for each place of business
33 of a retailer where a nicotine product is sold at retail, and for each licensed establishment
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 3 221
1 within which a retailer places a. Each vending machine that sells a nicotine product
2 pursuant to section 8 of this Act requires a separate license.
3 An application for a license required under this section must be made to the
4 Department of Revenue department, on forms prescribed by the secretary. The application
5 must contain:
6 (1) The contact information and date of birth of the applicant;
7 (2) The name and mailing address of the registered agent of the applicant;
8 (3) The physical address and mailing address of the place of business of the retailer;
9 and
10 (4)(3) All past and current violations of state or federal law by the applicant relating to
11 the sale, possession, or transportation of a nicotine product; and
12 (4) Any information required by the department pursuant to rules promulgated under
13 this chapter.
14 For retailers where at least fifty percent of the annual gross income in a year for
15 the place of business is estimated to be generated from the sales of nicotine products, the
16 application must be accompanied by a fee of five three hundred dollars.
17 For retailers where less than fifty percent of the annual gross income in a year for
18 the place of business is estimated to be generated from the sales of nicotine products, the
19 application must be accompanied by a fee of two hundred fifty dollars.
20 A vending machine retailer that places a vending machine in a licensed
21 establishment pursuant to section 8 of this Act, shall pay a fee of one hundred dollars for
22 each licensed establishment within which the retailer places a vending machine.
23 Section 5. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
24 A license issued under section 4 of this Act is valid through December thirtieth
25 thirty-first following the issuance of the license, unless the license is revoked sooner by
26 the secretary pursuant to this chapter. A license is valid for an additional three days if the
27 a pending application to renew a license is in the possession of the department before
28 midnight on the date of expiration and if the pending application is not subject to denial
29 pursuant to section 7 of this Act.
30 A license issued under section 4 of this Act may be transferred if the new licensee
31 obtains written approval from the department and is eligible for a license under this
32 chapter.
33 The transferee shall make an application in the same manner as provided in section
34 4, and the application must be acted upon in the same manner as an original application.
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 4 221
1 No transfer of any license to another person may be granted until all taxes incurred
2 by the transferor as a result of the operation of the licensed premises, including municipal
3 and state sales and use taxes, state reemployment assistance or unemployment insurance
4 tax, or any other state tax, are paid or are not delinquent. No transfer of any license to
5 another person may be granted until all property taxes which are the liability of the
6 licensee levied on the licensed premises are paid or are not delinquent.
7 Section 6. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
8 A licensee may apply to the Department of Revenue department for a renewal of
9 the license within:
10 (1) Thirty Sixty days prior to the expiration of the license; or
11 (2) Three days after the expiration of the license.
12 For retailers where at least fifty percent of the annual gross income in a year for
13 the place of business is generated from the sales of nicotine products, the renewal
14 application must be accompanied by a fee of five three hundred dollars.
15 For retailers where less than fifty percent of the annual gross income in a year for
16 the place of business is generated from the sales of nicotine products, the renewal
17 application must be accompanied by a fee of two hundred fifty dollars.
18 A vending machine retailer that places a vending machine in a licensed
19 establishment pursuant to section 8 of this Act, shall pay a fee of one hundred dollars for
20 each licensed establishment within which the retailer places a vending machine.
21 Section 7. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
22 The Department of Revenue department shall deny an application made under
23 section 4 or 6 of this Act if the applicant:
24 (1) The application includes Provides any false information;
25 (2) The applicant is Is under the age of twenty-one years; or
26 (3) The applicant has violated any state or federal law relating to the sale, possession,
27 or transportation of a nicotine productIs not current on the remittance of all
28 applicable state and local taxes; or
29 (4) Has been convicted of a felony in this or any other jurisdiction, unless at least ten
30 years have passed since satisfactory completion of the sentence or probation
31 imposed by the court in each felony conviction.
32 Section 8. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 5 221
1 A vending machine retailer may place a vending machine within an establishment
2 licensed pursuant to chapter 35-4, or within a licensed gaming establishment as defined
3 in § 42-7B-4, if the vending machine is placed in an area of the establishment in which
4 access is denied to persons under the age of twenty-one years.
5 A vending machine must be equipped with an age-verification system. Age
6 verification is required to purchase a nicotine product from the vending machine.
7 For purposes of this Act, the vending machine retailer is responsible for compliance
8 with all provisions of this Act. The establishment in which the vending machine is placed
9 is not a retailer or vending machine retailer, unless nicotine products are otherwise sold
10 at the establishment without the use of a vending machine.
11 Section 9. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
12 A licensee may not:
13 (1) Ship, or cause to be shipped, a nicotine product to an individual to be consumed
14 by the individual, except as otherwise provided in chapter 10-50C or under
15 provisions of House Bill 1220, as enacted by the One Hundred First Legislature;
16 (2) Sell, or offer to sell, a nicotine product to a person under the age of twenty-one
17 years;
18 (3) Sell, or offer to sell, a nicotine product in a vending machine, except as provided
19 in section 8 of this Act;
20 (4) Sell a nicotine product by phone, voice transmission, mail, internet, electronic-
21 application-based service, curbside pick-up, or by any third-party means, except
22 as otherwise provided in chapter 10-50C or under provisions of House Bill 1220,
23 as enacted by the One Hundred First Legislature;
24 (5) Provide free samples of nicotine products to an individual;
25 (6) Purchase a nicotine product from a person that is not a licensed distributor or
26 licensed wholesaler under chapter 10-50 or under the provisions of House Bill 1220,
27 as enacted by the One Hundred First Legislature; or
28 (7) Market, advertise, sell, Sell or cause to be sold a nicotine product where the
29 product, container, or packaging includes a video game or mobile game capable of
30 interfacing with an external gaming system or mobile application, or has a gaming
31 functionality.
32 A licensee is responsible for, and may be subject to enforcement action for, any
33 violation of this chapter committed by the licensee's employee, agency, agent, or clerk,
34 while acting within the scope of employment or agency.
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 6 221
1 For purposes of this section, a sale of a nicotine product from a vending machine
2 does not constitute a sale described under subdivision (4) of this section.
3 Section 10. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
4 A licensee shall post a sign, within plain view of any area on the premises where an individual
5 may purchase nicotine products, stating in text, at least one inch in height, that it is illegal to
6 sell nicotine products to any individual under the age of twenty-one.
7 Adjacent to the sign, the licensee shall display a valid license issued under this chapter.
8 A vending machine constitutes the point of sale for nicotine products sold from the vending
9 machine. The electronic display of the license and sign on the vending machine, as required
10 by this section, meets the requirements of this section.
11 Section 10. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
12 A licensee shall keep complete records of all nicotine products held in the licensee's
13 inventory and all nicotine products sold by the licensee, in a manner set forth in rules
14 promulgated by the secretary of the Department of Revenue pursuant to chapter 1-26.
15 The records must include information detailing the name, source, origin,
16 manufacturer, and address of the person supplying, and a copy of the purchase invoice,
17 of the nicotine products in the licensee's inventory.
18 The licensee shall preserve the records for three years.
19 If the records are not stored at the licensee's place of business, the licensee must,
20 upon request of the secretary, make the records available, in electronic form, within five
21 business days.
22 Nicotine products sold from, or contained in, a vending machine are inventory of
23 the licensed retailer, and are not the inventory of the establishment within which the
24 vending machine is placed. The requirements of this section apply only to the retailer,
25 and may be maintained at the retailer’s principal location.
26 The establishment within which the vending machine is placed is not subject to the
27 requirements of this section, but must allow access to the vending machine for purposes
28 of compliance with this chapter.
29 Section 11. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 7 221
1 The secretary of the Department of Revenue or an agent of the secretary may,
2 during normal business hours, inspect the records and premises of any licensee, and may
3 conduct an investigation to determine whether the licensee has violated any provision of
4 this chapter or rule promulgated thereunder. The secretary or agent of the secretary shall
5 conduct an inspection or investigation under this section, in accordance with rules
6 promulgated by the secretary pursuant to chapter 1-26.
7 An establishment within which a vending machine is placed is not subject to the
8 provisions of this section solely for the purpose of determining whether the retailer has
9 violated any provisions of this chapter or any rule promulgated thereunder.
10 Section 12. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
11 Except as otherwise provided in this section, the secretary of the Department of
12 Revenue, or an agent of the secretary, shall conduct an inspection of each licensee at least
13 once every two years. If the secretary receives information of a violation by any licensee
14 of any provision of this chapter, the secretary must investigate the alleged violation. If
15 there is substantial evidence to support that a violation of any provision of this chapter
16 has occurred, the secretary must proceed in accordance with the provisions of this
17 chapter.
18 If a licensee has been determined by the department to have violated any provision
19 of this chapter, the secretary or an agent of the secretary must conduct an inspection of
20 the licensee within six months of the determination.
21 Section 13. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
22 The Department of Revenue shall publish on the department's website the following
23 information for each licensee:
24 (1) The licensee's name;
25 (2) The name and mailing address of the registered agent of the licensee;
26 (3) The physical address of the licensee's place of business;
27 (4) The registered agent; and
28 (5) The date on which the license was initially issued.
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 8 221
1 If a licensee is determined to have violated a provision of this chapter or chapter 34-46, the
2 secretary of the department must publish notice of the violation on the department's website.
3 Section 13. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
4 If a licensee is determined to have violated a provision of sections 8 to 11 10,
5 inclusive, of this Act or a provision of chapter 34-46, the secretary of the Department of
6 Revenue must assess a penalty according to the following schedule:
7 (1) For a first violation, a fine not exceeding five hundred dollars;
8 (2) For a second violation within a thirty-six-month period, a fine of one thousand
9 dollars;
10 (3) For a third violation within a thirty-six-month period, a fine of two thousand dollars,
11 and in addition to the fine assessed under this subdivision the licensee:
12 (a) May not sell, or offer to sell, a nicotine product for the following thirty days; and
13 (b) Must post a sign adjacent to the sign required in section 10 of this Act, stating in
14 text at least one inch in height that due to a violation of state law, nicotine products
15 may not be sold at this location at this time; and the secretary shall suspend the
16 license for thirty days;
17 (4) For a fourth violation within a thirty-six-month period, a fine of five thousand five
18 hundred dollars, and in addition to the fine assessed under this subdivision, the
19 secretary shall revoke the license.
20 Except as otherwise provided in this section, the secretary may, in accordance with
21 chapter 1-26, revoke or suspend a license issued under this chapter for failure of the
22 licensee to comply with a provision of this chapter or rules promulgated thereunder, or if
23 the licensee is convicted of a felony.
24 A fine assessed under this section is due within thirty days of the department
25 providing notice of the fine to the licensee.
26 Section 14. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
27 A fine assessed under section 15 of this Act is due within thirty days of the Department of
28 Revenue providing notice of the fine to the licensee.
29 If the department determines that a licensee has failed to pay any fine, fee, or tax imposed
30 by this chapter, or any other fine, fee, or tax imposed by this state or a political subdivision
31 of this state by the due date, the secretary must suspend the license of the retailer until the
32 payment has been made.
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 9 221
1 Section 14. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
2 If the license of a retailer is revoked pursuant to section 15 13 of this Act, the
3 retailer must destroy:
4 (1) Destroy all nicotine products possessed by the retailer, at the time of the
5 revocation, in accordance with all state and federal requirements related to
6 hazardous materials; or
7 (2) Return all nicotine products to the licensed distributor or licensed wholesaler under
8 chapter 10-50 or under the provisions of House Bill 1220, as enacted by the One
9 Hundred First Legislature, from which the nicotine products were purchased by the
10 licensee.
11 The retailer shall submit verification of the destruction or return to the Department
12 of Revenue department, in a manner provided in rules promulgated by the secretary of
13 the department.
14 A retailer who fails to comply with this section within seven sixty days from the
15 revocation of the license is subject to a fine of five thousand dollars, imposed by the
16 department.
17 Section 15. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
18 If a licensee is determined to have violated any provision of this chapter, the
19 licensee may appeal an action or decision of the secretary of the Department of Revenue,
20 in the same manner as provided in chapter 1-26.
21 Section 16. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
22 The Department of Revenue department shall promulgate rules, in accordance with
23 chapter 1-26, to:
24 (1) Establish a procedure for an initial and a renewal license application under this
25 chapter, and the information required in the application;
26 (2) Provide for the manner in which nicotine products must be destroyed or returned
27 and the manner in which verification of the destruction or return must be
28 submitted;
29 (3) Provide the process for assessing and collecting fines under this chapter;
30 (4) Establish standards for the keeping of records, as required in section 11 10 of this
31 Act; and
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 10 221
1 (5) Establish a process for the inspection of records and premises, as authorized in
2 section 12 11 of this Act.
3 Section 17. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
4 A retailer who sells a nicotine product in this state, without a license issued
5 pursuant to this chapter, is subject to a fine of five thousand hundred dollars, per day,
6 imposed by the Department of Revenue department, except as provided in section 5 of
7 this Act.
8 Section 18. That a NEW SECTION be added to a NEW CHAPTER in title 10:
9 There is created a nicotine enforcement fund. The Department of Revenue
10 department shall administer the fund. The purpose of the fund is to defray expenses
11 associated with the enforcement of this chapter.
12 Moneys collected under this chapter must be forwarded to the state treasurer to
13 be deposited into the fund. Interest on moneys credited to the fund must remain in the
14 fund.
15 Expenditures from the fund must be budgeted through the general appropriation
16 bill.
17 Section 19. That § 34-46-2 be AMENDED:
18 34-46-2. The following actions are unlawful:
19 (1) To knowingly sell or distribute a tobacco product nicotine product, as defined in
20 section 2 of this Act, to a person under the age of twenty-one;
21 (2) To purchase or attempt to purchase, to receive or attempt to receive, to possess,
22 or to consume a tobacco nicotine product, as defined in section 2 of this Act, if a
23 person is under the age of twenty-one;
24 (3) To purchase a tobacco product nicotine product, as defined in section 2 of this Act,
25 on behalf of, or to give a tobacco nicotine product to, any person under the age of
26 twenty-one;
27 (4)(3) To sell cigarettes nicotine products, as defined in section 2 of this Act, other than
28 in an unopened package originating with the manufacturer and depicting the
29 warning labels required by federal law;
30 (5)(4) To sell tobacco products nicotine products, as defined in section 2 of this Act,
31 through a vending machine located in a place other than a place that is open to
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 11 221
1 the public but to which persons under the age of twenty-one are denied access at
2 all times, except as otherwise provided in section 8 of this Act;
3 (6)(5) To sell cigarettes or smokeless tobacco, or both, nicotine products, as defined in
4 section 2 of this Act, through a self-service display other than a display that is:
5 (a) A vending machine permitted under subdivision (5) of this section; or
6 (b) Located in a tobacco speciality store; or
7 (7)(6) To distribute tobacco product samples samples of nicotine products, as defined in
8 section 2 of this Act, in or on a public street, sidewalk, or park that is within five
9 hundred feet of a playground, school, or other facility when the facility is being
10 used primarily by persons under the age of twenty-one.
11 Section 20. That § 34-46-2.2 be AMENDED:
12 34-46-2.2. A Except as otherwise provided in this section, a merchant shall
13 conspicuously post a notice, on the merchant's premises, stating in text at least one inch
14 in height, that "No no person under the age of 21twenty-one may be sold tobacco
15 products."
16 Any owner, lessee, or person having control of any cigarette vending machine shall
17 post, in a conspicuous place on each machine in use within the state, a warning which
18 shall be printed in bold type letters each of which shall be at least one-half inch high and
19 which shall be kept in easily legible form and repair stating:
20 "Any person under 21 years of age is forbidden by law to purchase cigarettes from
21 this machine." or nicotine products, as defined in section 2 of this Act.
22 For purposes of this section, the notice may be displayed electronically on a
23 vending machine.
24 Adjacent to the sign, the licensee shall display a valid license issued under this
25 chapter. A vending machine constitutes the point of sale for nicotine products sold from
26 the vending machine.
27 Section 21. That § 34-46-3 be AMENDED:
28 34-46-3. Each county state's attorney or a local law enforcement officer
29 designated by the state's attorney shall annually conduct unannounced, random
30 inspections at various locations where tobacco nicotine products, as defined in section 2
31 of this Act, are sold or distributed to ensure compliance with this chapter. Persons under
32 the age of twenty-one may be enlisted to test compliance with this chapter. Such persons
33 may be used to test compliance with this chapter only if the testing is conducted under
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

221F 12 221
1 the supervision of the county state's attorney or a local law enforcement officer designated
2 by the state's attorney and written parental consent has been provided. Any other use of
3 persons under the age of twenty-one to test compliance with this chapter is unlawful and
4 the persons responsible for such use are subject to the penalties prescribed in § 34-46-5.
5 Any evidence of a violation of this chapter or sections 2 to 18, inclusive, of this Act,
6 must be submitted to the secretary of the Department of Revenue.
7 Section 22. That § 34-46-21 be AMENDED:
8 34-46-21. No person may sell a vapor nicotine product, as defined in section 2 of
9 this Act, other than in an unopened package originating with the manufacturer and
10 depicting the warning labels required by federal law, or sell a vapor product through self-
11 service display other than a display that is:
12 (1) A vending machine permitted under subdivision 34-46-2(5); or
13 (2) Located in a tobacco specialty store.
14 A violation of person who violates this section is a Class 2 misdemeanor. A person
15 is not liable for more than one violation of this section on a single day subject to a fine of
16 two hundred fifty dollars, imposed by the Department of Revenue. Each violation is subject
17 to a fine.
18 Section 23. This Act is effective beginning January 1, 2027.
